<cell id="cell-0"><language>kotlin</language>// Kotlin notebook
import jline.*
import jline.lang.*
import jline.lang.nodes.*
import jline.lang.processes.*
import jline.lang.constant.*
import jline.solvers.jmt.*
import jline.util.matrix.*</cell id="cell-0">
<cell id="cell-1"><language>kotlin</language>// Example: M/M/1 Queue with Exponential Impatience (Reneging)
//
// This example demonstrates customer impatience in a simple M/M/1 queue.
// Jobs arrive according to a Poisson process and have exponentially
// distributed service times. If a job waits too long in the queue, it
// reneges (abandons) according to an exponential patience distribution.
//
// Model:
// - Single queue with FCFS scheduling
// - Exponential service time (rate = 1.0)
// - Exponential arrival process (rate = 0.8)
// - Exponential patience/reneging time (rate = 0.5)

val model = Network("M/M/1 with Exponential Impatience")</cell id="cell-1">
<cell id="cell-2"><language>kotlin</language>// Define nodes
val source = Source(model, "Source")
val queue1 = Queue(model, "Queue1", SchedStrategy.FCFS)
val sink = Sink(model, "Sink")

// Define job class
val jobclass = OpenClass(model, "Class1", 0)</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"><language>kotlin</language>// Set service times
queue1.setService(jobclass, Exp(1.0))  // Mean service time = 1.0

// Set arrival rate
source.setArrival(jobclass, Exp(0.8))  // Arrival rate = 0.8

// Set patience distribution (queue-specific)
// Jobs will renege after an exponentially distributed time with rate 0.5
queue1.setPatience(jobclass, Exp(0.5))  // Mean patience = 2.0</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><language>kotlin</language>// Define routing
val P = model.initRoutingMatrix()
P.set(jobclass, jobclass, source, queue1, 1.0)   // Source -> Queue1
P.set(jobclass, jobclass, queue1, sink, 1.0)     // Queue1 -> Sink
model.link(P)</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5"><language>kotlin</language>// Solve with JMT
println("This example shows a simple M/M/1 queue with exponential impatience.")
println("Jobs will abandon (renege) the queue after waiting for an exponential time.")
println()
println("Model parameters:")
println("  - Arrival rate: 0.8")
println("  - Service rate: 1.0")
println("  - Patience rate: 0.5 (mean patience = 2.0)")
println()

val solver = JMT(model, "seed", 23000, "verbose", true, "keep", true, "samples", 100000)
val avgTable = solver.avgTable
avgTable.print()

println()
println("Note: The queue length and response time should be lower than a standard M/M/1")
println("      due to jobs reneging when their patience expires.")</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"><language>markdown</language>## M/M/1 Queue with Exponential Impatience

This notebook demonstrates customer impatience in a simple M/M/1 queueing system. Jobs that wait too long in the queue will **renege** (abandon the queue) according to an exponential patience distribution.

### Model Structure
- **Single queue** with FCFS scheduling
- **Exponential arrivals**: Poisson process with rate 0.8
- **Exponential service**: Service rate 1.0
- **Exponential patience**: Reneging rate 0.5 (mean patience = 2.0)

### Impatience Mechanism
Each job has a patience timer that starts when it enters the queue. If the job's patience expires before it begins service, it abandons (reneges from) the queue and exits the system.

### Parameters
- Arrival rate: 0.8 jobs/time unit
- Service rate: 1.0 (mean service time = 1.0)
- Patience rate: 0.5 (mean patience time = 2.0)

### Expected Results
Compared to a standard M/M/1 queue without impatience, this system should show:
- **Lower queue lengths**: Jobs leave due to reneging
- **Lower response times**: Only more patient jobs remain in the queue
- **Job losses**: Some jobs abandon before receiving service

This is a fundamental model for studying customer abandonment in service systems like call centers.</cell id="cell-6">